(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
== Chapter 1: A History of Dispossession ==

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;_GoBack&amp;#34;/}}Christopher Columbus’s arrival marked the beginning of a new era of genocidal violence on Native Americans ===

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== AND ===

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== The legacy of dispossession continues today. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Indigenous lands are being isolated in policymaking discussionson NOW how we can increase energy production. Even within these policy conversations, indigenous communities are divided by those who can hold land in trust and those who cannot. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Press Release 12**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Office of Hawaiian Senator Daniel Akaka, 2-16-12, [[http:~~/~~/akaka.senate.gov/print-release.cfm?method=releases.viewandid=6b083a29-9fd7-4103-8c87-b1e41bc5fd3f&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://akaka.senate.gov/print-release.cfm?method=releases.viewandid=6b083a29-9fd7-4103-8c87-b1e41bc5fd3f]]) PM

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)WASHINGTON D.C. - (%%)__**U.**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__**policies that improve energy development on Native lands.&amp;#34;**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== This turn to indigenous communities, lands and resources for increased U.S. domestic energy production is not innocent or new. American energy production and consumption is intrinsically linked to violent colonialisms. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Thomas-Muller**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__** 20**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**05**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Clayton, Cree Indian and a Native energy organizer for the Indigenous Environmental Network, //Moving the Movement for Transportation Justice// Vol 12, No1, [[http:~~/~~/urbanhabitat.org/node/307&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://urbanhabitat.org/node/307]]) PM

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__**The link between unsustainable energy consumption in the**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)our attitudes towards the sacredness of Mother Earth.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== U.S. civil society’s comportment towards energy production is premised on the structural imposition of an epistemology of “possession”—the belief that humans have a right to possess and dispose of the land and its “resources” as they see fit. The mode of relationality inherent within the paradigm of Settlerism is tantamount to ontological degradation and responsible for the genocide of indigenous populations. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Wilderson 10**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Frank, MFA @ Columbia University in Fiction Writing, Ph.D. @ University of California, Berkeley in Rhetoric/Film Studies, Prof @ UC Irvine, //Red, White, and Black: Cinema and the Structure of U.S. Antagonisms//, p176-178~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__**&amp;#34;Savage&amp;#34; sovereignty qua land is distinguished**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**a struggle to re-Indigenize the land**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Genocidal assaults on indigenous populations set the foundation for serial policy failure in imperialist campaigns abroad—risks extinction. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Street 4**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Paul Street, phD in History from Binghamton, march 11, “Those Who Deny the Crimes of the Past,” [[http:~~/~~/www.zcommunications.org/those-who-deny-the-crimes-of-the-past-by-paul-street&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.zcommunications.org/those-who-deny-the-crimes-of-the-past-by-paul-street]] ~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)It is especially important to appreciate the significance

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)civilized people than those who came to destroy.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== An analysis of oppression that neglects a paradigmatic analysis of indigenous genocide has failed to come to prior material conditions—indigenous criticism is the first priority ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Churchill 3**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__** **__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)(Ward, ex-Prof of Ethnic Studies @ U of Colorado, Acts of Rebellion: The Ward Churchill Reader, p 263-5~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)I am here, however, as may

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**to every indigenous nation within its purported borders**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== Thus, JMU BM affirms the resolution as a site of interrogation to analyze the historical paradigm of Settlerism that undergirds energy production in the United States. ===

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
== Chapter 2: Lay the West to Rest ==

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== We don’t defend the instrumental adoption of energy production—instead, we affirm the resolution as a locus to trace the lineage of political repugnancies in the U.S. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Churchill 3**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Ward, Acts of Rebellion: The Ward Churchill Reader, p. xv-xvii) PM

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__**The question arises of how best to approach**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)that made on 9-1-1.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== Our advocacy stands in an antagonistic relation to civil society—any alternative that tries to take a middle ground is complicit. ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Wilderson 10**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Frank, MFA @ Columbia University in Fiction Writing, Ph.D. @ University of California, Berkeley in Rhetoric/Film Studies, Prof @ UC Irvine, //Red, White, and Black: Cinema and the Structure of U.S. Antagonisms//, p6-7~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)Semiotics and linguistics teach us that when we

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)both political common sense and in political cinema?

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Energy production is a vital starting point to address legacies of dispossession ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Powell**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 0.6em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**10**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Dana E., Assistant Professor of Anthropology, Ph.D. at University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill, and D.J. Long, “Landscapes of Power: Renewable Energy Activism in Diné Bikéyah,”, Indians and Energy: Exploitation and Opportunity in the American Southwest.)ERM

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**Contemporary debates**__(%%)__** on the Navajo Nation (% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)form a(%%)**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**deeply cultural, political spiritual, and social.**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Debate is key—repudiation of Euro-American imperialism in academia helps establish modes of knowledge production that file away at systems of domination ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Dei 2**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (George Sefa, Professor of Sociology and Equity Studies@ Ontario Institute for Studies in Education of the University of Toronto, “Rethinking the Role of Indigenous Knowledges in the Academy,” The Research Network for New Approaches to Lifelong Learning, [[http:~~/~~/www.nall.ca/res/58GeorgeDei.pdf&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.nall.ca/res/58GeorgeDei.pdf]] ~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)Ultimately, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**we have to consider the role**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)systems in our academic communicative and pedagogical practices.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Reformism’s attempt to assimilate natives into its lattice of doctrine and laws fails—Leftists reassurances have historically resulted in hacks from the military industrial complex being sent from Washington to dissolve native struggles ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__**Churchill 3 **__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)(Ward, “Acts of Rebellion: The Ward Churchill Reader,” Questia, Page 110~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Although the United States did not have to**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**of native people and backed by the army**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 0.6em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== The 1AC’s gesture towards impossible realism is productive—you should be skeptical of arguments refuting solvency for our method ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Churchill 96**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Ward, ex-Prof of Ethnic Studies @ U of Colorado, “From a Native Son”, p.85-90~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**The question which**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) inevitably (% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**arises with regard to**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)it time we all worked on attaining it?

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== While each indigenous collective has different histories and traditions, strategic essentialism is key—reinforcing the common experience of Eurocentric domination is key to prevent atomization that mystifies the violence of colonialism ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Churchill 8**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Ward, ex-Prof of Ethnic Studies @ U of Colorado, “I Am Indigenist,” November 18, [[http:~~/~~/www.zcommunications.org/i-am-indigenist-by-ward-churchill&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.zcommunications.org/i-am-indigenist-by-ward-churchill]] ~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)The manifestation of indigenism in North America has

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**five centuries of [Eurocentric] domination**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %).9

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Speaking for groups by acknowledging suffering has been empirically effective in the context of indigeneity ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Alcoff 92**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)(Linda, Syracuse Philosophy, “The Problem of Speaking for Others” [[http:~~/~~/www.alcoff.com/content/speaothers.html&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.alcoff.com/content/speaothers.html]] ~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)While the &amp;#34;Charge of Reductionism&amp;#34; response

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**AND**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #c0c0c0&amp;#34; %)__**effects can be garnered in no other way**__(%%)__**.**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Policy Debate is skewed towards Western ways of knowing—it compartmentalizes arguments and privileges the tit-for-tat “objectivity” of the line-by-line instead of viewing our speeches as an interconnected, coherent whole. The idea that negs can “kick” arguments at any point in the debate is mired in an idea of neutral consensus building that crowds out an indigenization of the debate space ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Walker**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 0.6em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**4**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)(Polly O, is of Cherokee and Anglo descent and holds a PhD in conflict transformation from the University of Queensland in Australia. “Decolonizing conflict resolution: addressing the ontological violence of westernization,” The American Indian Quarterly 28.3and4 (2004) 527-549~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**The atomistic conceptualizations on which**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) these (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Western models**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)AND

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)conflict (Burton 1996, 60–61).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
=== Unproblematized use of Western norms for conflict resolution commits ontological violence and trains us to be future colonizers ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(192, 192, 192)&amp;#34; %)__**Walker 4**__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %) (Polly O, is of Cherokee and Anglo descent and holds a PhD in conflict transformation from the University of Queensland in Australia. “Decolonizing conflict resolution: addressing the ontological violence of westernization,” The American Indian Quarterly 28.3and4 (2004) 527-549~/~/shree)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


