</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/James%20Madison/pages/Bosley-Miller%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/24"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/James%20Madison/pages/Bosley-Miller%20Aff/objects/Admin.EntryClass/24/properties"/><id>opencaselist:James Madison.Bosley-Miller Aff:d0a05e75-70f2-4221-8d8f-479408ccc1d5</id><guid>d0a05e75-70f2-4221-8d8f-479408ccc1d5</guid><pageId>opencaselist:James Madison.Bosley-Miller Aff</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>James Madison</space><pageName>Bosley-Miller Aff</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>24</number><headline>Contention One – The Foundational Violence of US Energy Policy
What drives U.S. energy policy, why now? On the heels of the renewed war in Iraq, War on Terror, war in Afghanistan, economic recessions, failed and slowing recoveries, increasing signs of worldwide environmental destruction and global economic interdependence; the U.S. has determined again to renew interest in increasing energy production to meet American demand while simultaneously decreasing dependence on outside energy sources and experimenting with less ecologically violent forms of production. 
In response to these exigencies, the affirmative is asked to increase energy production in the U.S. While we affirm that action is desperately needed, we must know that such action is never as simple as the demand asks. 
 
One needs look no further than how the U.S. is responding to the pressure for increased so-called “domestic energy” production through energy imperialism by relying on legal divisions in indigenous communities
Press Release 12 (Office of Hawaiian Senator Daniel Akaka, http://akaka.senate.gov/print-release.cfm?method=releases.viewandid=6b083a29-9fd7-4103-8c87-b1e41bc5fd3f) PM

WASHINGTON D.C. - U.S. Senator Daniel K. Akaka …improve energy development on Native lands.&amp;#34;

 
This turn to indigenous communities, lands and resources for increased U.S. domestic energy production is not innocent or new. American energy production and consumption is intrinsically linked to violent colonialisms.  
Thomas-Muller 05 (Clayton, Cree Indian and a Native energy organizer for the Indigenous Environmental Network, Moving the Movement for Transportation Justice Vol 12, No1, http://urbanhabitat.org/node/307) PM

The link between unsustainable energy consumption … in our attitudes towards the sacredness of Mother Earth.



U.S. energy policy, domestic production and indigenous lands are necessarily linked together in a sovereign relationship. Which lands fall under U.S. jurisdiction, who has authority over those lands, what counts as resources, even if sovereignty is possible are all prior questions to answering if or how we can increase energy production in the U.S. 
Current U.S. policy with and over indigenous communities is rooted in a foundational moment of sovereign violence, a zone of in-distinction where they are both inside and outside of U.S. jurisdiction. Indigenous peoples are included in U.S. doctrine, legislation and court standings in so much as they are excluded, a negative presence on which the rest of American society is built. 
As the discussion of energy production policy demonstrates, territory and geopolitics makes this form of sovereign relationship foundational to understanding all U.S.–Indigenous relationships and policies. The initial U.S. move to declare sovereign authority over land already occupied by indigenous communities has made possible the violent history of energy policy. 
Moreover, this sovereign relationship is meta-political. This is not an issue of specific content, issues or policies but of the very foundation for what constitutes “the political.” Rather than focusing on the race or culture of indigenous communities, we must trace U.S. imperialist violence to sovereignty. 
Rifkin 09 (Mark, Professor of English at UNC-Greensboro, “Indigenizing Agamben: Rethinking sovereignty in light of the peculiar status of native peoples,” Cultural Critique 73, Fall, p. 89-91) PM 

What does “sovereignty” mean in the context …, the “peculiar”-ization of Native peoples.

2012 legislation and court decisions have reaffirmed the exceptional and paradoxical space of indigenous communities relative to the United States. Sovereignty is the key issue that must be grappled with else imperialist violence will continue.
Wilkins 12 (David, McNight Presidential Professorship in American Indian Studies at the University of Minnesota, “Federal Assumptions that Enfeeble Native America,” Indian Country Today, http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/ict_sbc/federal-assumptions-that-enfeeble-native-america) PM

Native American people and the distinctive …and the larger state and society.

This discussion does not occur on a neutral playing field; Elyssa and I both benefit from our position of settler privilege on stolen Algonquian land. However, in an attempt to de-hegemonize our privilege:
 
JMU BM affirms that the United States federal government should remove all restrictions on Native American energy production in the United States for: coal, natural gas, nuclear power, oil, solar power, wind power. 

Contention Two – Interrupting US Energy Imperialism 
While we don’t defend an instrumental adoption of the plan, the 1AC functions as a discursive entry point to trace and call into question the sovereign violence that founds U.S. energy policy and energy production. Voting affirmative uses the language and tools of sovereignty to highlight the contradictions, paradoxes and state of exception that indigenous communities exist in with relation to U.S. energy policy. 
While this strategy risks violence, the countercitation of sovereignty highlights the groundless of existing U.S. policy which can only incorporate indigenous communities through sovereignty violence. Our discursive entry opens the indigenous-sovereign state of exception for new possible relationships. 
Rifkin 09 (Mark, Professor of English at UNC-Greensboro, “Indigenizing Agamben: Rethinking sovereignty in light of the peculiar status of native peoples,” Cultural Critique 73, Fall, p. 108-115) PM 

This effort to find a way to ameliorate the force …institutional structures of the settler-state.

Debate is key—repudiation of Euro-American imperialism in academia helps establish modes of knowledge production that file away at systems of domination
Dei 2 (George Sefa, Professor of Sociology and Equity Studies@ Ontario Institute for Studies in Education of the University of Toronto, “Rethinking the Role of Indigenous Knowledges in the Academy,” The Research Network for New Approaches to Lifelong Learning, http://www.nall.ca/res/58GeorgeDei.pdf //shree) 

Ultimately, we have to consider the role of Indigenous … our academic communicative and pedagogical practices.



 
Speaking for groups by acknowledging suffering has been empirically effective in the context of indigeneity
Alcoff 92 
(Linda, Syracuse Philosophy, “The Problem of Speaking for Others” http://www.alcoff.com/content/speaothers.html //shree)

While the &amp;#34;Charge of Reductionism&amp;#34; response has been …can be garnered in no other way.


 
We must abandon band-aid solutions for an epistemic overhaul
Deloria Jr. 99 (Vine, For This Land: Writing on Religion in America, p. 101-7) PM 

But this replacement only begins the task of liberation… reasoning are the primary tools For gaining knowledge.  


Case outweighs any risk of co-option
Koukkanen 3 (Rauna Kuokkanen, from Samiland, has recently completed her PhD at the University of British Columbia on Indigenous epistemes and the academy. In January 2005 she will commence her post-doctoral fellowship with a collaborative research project on globalization and autonomy at McMaster University.  “Toward a New Relation of Hospitality in the Academy,” The American Indian Quarterly 27.1and2 (2003) 267-295 //shree)

